article.headline: Monarchs drop finale going into postseason
article.linkText: Jackson takes scoring title as Seattle wins finale
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Lauren Jackson locked up the WNBA scoring title.
Could the MVP award be next?

Jackson scored 18 points and Tonya Massaline hit all four of her
second-half shots as the Seattle Storm beat the playoff-bound
Sacramento Monarchs 70-57 Monday night in the final game of the
WNBA regular season.

Jackson averaged 21.2 points a game this summer to win the WNBA
scoring title. When the subject came up in the locker room, she
broke into a big smile as she tried to downplay its significance.

"It wasn't important," Jackson said through an embarrassed
grin. "It's just a scoring title, but I guess it's pretty cool."

Her 698 points were the second highest single-season total in
league history. Minnesota guard Katie Smith scored 739 points in
2001.

"Scoring's not the only thing, but you can't look past it,"
Storm guard Sue Bird said. "It says a lot about a person when they
can come out every single night, facing double-teams and
triple-teams and still get 20."

Tangela Smith led Sacramento (19-15) with 13 points while
Yolanda Griffith scored 12. The Monarchs finished the regular
season 12-4 under interim coach John Whisenant and will open the
playoffs Friday at home against Houston.

"We have to put this behind us," Whisenant said. "I would
have much preferred if we would have continued to play well. We're
struggling offensively, and we are just not sharp."

Sandy Brondello scored 13 for the Storm (18-16), which missed
the Western Conference playoffs after losing five straight down the
stretch. Seattle rebounded to win its final two games.

"Usually you don't play well when there's nothing riding on it,
but we wanted to end on a good note," said Bird, who had eight
assists. "We played hard. We played a good team, a team that is my
pick to be the WNBA champion."

The Monarchs led 36-35 until the Storm used a 6-0 burst to force
a Sacramento timeout with 12:37 remaining. Seattle kept it going
after the break, with Massaline scoring seven points in a 13-6
burst.

"Tonya's been big the last two nights. She's done a great
job," Bird said.

Massaline finished with nine points, and her 3-pointer with 8:25
to play put the Storm ahead 54-42. Nothing could slow Seattle.

"The defense was something we struggled with in the first half,
but they weren't able to hit shots in the second half and we could
stay in our zone a little more," Donovan said.

After another timeout at the 8-minute mark, Alisa Burras had a
putback and two free throws, Jackson hit from inside and Tully
Bevilaqua added a 3-pointer to stretch the lead to 63-42 with 6:05
on the clock.

"It this game did mean something, then we sure wouldn't be in
the playoffs," Griffith said.

Jackson had the scoring title locked up before tipoff.

Chamique Holdsclaw, who ranked second in the league at 20.5
points a game, left Washington's game at Detroit with an injured
left knee after scoring 14 points, not enough to cut into Jackson's
lead for the WNBA scoring title.

"That's one player who has worked hard every step of the way,"
Donovan said. "She never takes a day off. She never takes a minute
off in practice. When she sits down, she is truly hurt and can't
go."
